hands_on_practices.solution:
The relevant physical principle is Ohm’s law across the series (access) resistance: the voltage drop due to the current flowing through the access resistance is given by
$$
V_{error} = I_{peak} R_{a}.
$$
With $I_{peak} = -500 \text{ pA} = -500 \times 10^{-12} \text{ A}$ and $R_{a} = 20 \text{ M}\Omega = 20 \times 10^{6} \ \Omega$, we compute
$$
V_{error} = \left(-500 \times 10^{-12}\right)\left(20 \times 10^{6}\right) \ \text{V}
= (-500 \cdot 20) \times 10^{-12+6} \ \text{V}
= -10000 \times 10^{-6} \ \text{V}
= -10 \times 10^{-3} \ \text{V}
= -10 \ \text{mV}.
$$
Thus, the voltage drop across the access resistance at the peak inward current is $-10 \ \text{mV}$. The magnitude of the deviation is $10 \ \text{mV}$; the negative sign reflects the inward (negative) current direction under the chosen sign convention.
